## Git & GitHub Workflow

### Initial Project Setup

1. **Git Configuration - Check Before Committing**
   ```bash
   # ALWAYS verify git config before first commit
   git config user.name
   git config user.email
   
   # If wrong account, set local config:
   # Personal projects:
   git config user.name "Jordan Cheung"
   git config user.email "jcheung611@gmail.com"
   
   # Work projects (DoorDash):
   git config user.name "jordan-cheung-dd"
   git config user.email "jordan.cheung@doordash.com"
   ```

2. **Repository Creation Checklist**
   - [ ] Create `.gitignore` FIRST (before git init)
   - [ ] Create `.env.example` (never commit `.env`)
   - [ ] Create comprehensive `README.md`
   - [ ] Create `LICENSE` (MIT preferred)
   - [ ] Create `.cursorrules` (this file!)
   - [ ] Initialize git: `git init`
   - [ ] Verify author config
   - [ ] Make initial commit
   - [ ] Create GitHub repo (user creates, AI guides)
   - [ ] Push to GitHub

3. **GitHub Authentication**
   ```bash
   # Check current auth status
   gh auth status
   
   # Login if needed (user will do OAuth flow)
   gh auth login
   
   # Setup git to use GitHub CLI
   gh auth setup-git
   ```

### Commit Standards

1. **Commit Frequency**
   - Commit after each meaningful feature/change
   - Don't let uncommitted work pile up
   - Use descriptive commit messages

2. **Commit Message Format**
   ```
   Brief summary (50 chars or less)
   
   Detailed explanation if needed:
   - What changed
   - Why it changed
   - Any breaking changes
   
   Optional footer (refs, co-authors, etc.)
   ```

3. **When to Commit**
   - ‚úÖ After completing a feature
   - ‚úÖ After fixing a bug
   - ‚úÖ After major refactoring
   - ‚úÖ Before switching tasks
   - ‚úÖ After updating documentation
   - ‚ùå Don't commit broken code
   - ‚ùå Don't commit secrets/API keys

